        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p><strong>Search Quality Rater Guidelines</strong> is a 170+ page document Google provides to human evaluators who assess search results and websites. It defines content quality through frameworks like <strong>E-E-A-T and YMYL</strong>. Raters don't change rankings directly — their feedback trains Google's algorithms to detect the same quality patterns automatically.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Document length</div>
            <div class="tms-value">170+ pages</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">General Marketing</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Key framework</div>
            <div class="tms-value">E-E-A-T + YMYL</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Intermediate</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">Most SEOs track rankings. The smarter move is reading the document Google uses to define what "good" looks like before it trains the algorithm. That document is the Search Quality Rater Guidelines — and it's publicly available.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What are the Search Quality Rater Guidelines?</h2>
        <p>The Search Quality Rater Guidelines (also called the QRG or Quality Rater Guidelines) is a manual Google distributes to thousands of contracted human evaluators worldwide. These evaluators — called Quality Raters — review search results and web pages and score them using the frameworks in the document.</p>
        <p>Raters are given two main evaluation tasks:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Page Quality (PQ) Rating</strong> — evaluators assess a page's quality from Lowest to Highest based on content harmfulness, trustworthiness, and genuine value.</li>
          <li><strong>Needs Met (NM) Rating</strong> — evaluators assess how effectively a result satisfies the user's query, from "Fails to Meet" to "Fully Meets."</li>
        </ul>
        <p>The key insight: Quality Raters do not change any rankings. Their scores generate training data that helps Google refine the machine learning models powering its ranking algorithms. When Google launches a Core Update or the Helpful Content System, it is partly checking whether the update produces results that would score well with raters.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Google's stance</div>
          <p>Google publishes the full guidelines publicly. The document is updated regularly — major annual revisions plus smaller changes throughout the year. The December 2022 update added "Experience" to create E-E-A-T; 2023 updates included explicit guidance on AI-generated content.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why the Search Quality Rater Guidelines matter for SEO</h2>
        <p>The guidelines are the closest thing to a direct statement from Google about what quality means. Every major algorithm update — Core Updates, Helpful Content, Product Reviews — is designed to automatically detect what human raters evaluate manually. If you understand the guidelines, you understand where the algorithm is pointed.</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Algorithm alignment.</strong> Core Updates specifically target the gap between what raters would score highly and what the algorithm was ranking. Aligning your content with rater expectations is aligning with future algorithm signals.</li>
          <li><strong>E-E-A-T signals become concrete.</strong> The guidelines define exactly what "expertise" and "trustworthiness" mean in practice — author bios, external reputation, cited sources, site security. These become actionable content and design requirements.</li>
          <li><strong>YMYL content gets a clear playbook.</strong> If your site covers health, finance, legal, or safety topics, the guidelines prescribe the specific quality bar you must clear — and why thin or AI-generated content in these categories is graded harshest.</li>
          <li><strong>Content gap identification.</strong> The Needs Met framework reveals when a result "Fully Meets" vs "Partially Meets" a query — a practical lens for evaluating whether your own content truly satisfies the user's full intent.</li>
          <li><strong>Reputation matters explicitly.</strong> The guidelines instruct raters to research a website's external reputation. This makes off-page authority — press mentions, reviews, citations — a ranked quality signal, not just a link-building tactic.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How Quality Raters use the guidelines</h2>
        <p>Raters receive a query and a set of search results. For each result, they assess the page against the guidelines using structured rating scales. The process follows a repeatable pattern:</p>
        <ol>
          <li>Identify the main content, supplementary content, and ads on the page.</li>
          <li>Determine the page's purpose — is it designed to help users or to deceive or generate ad revenue without genuine value?</li>
          <li>Evaluate E-E-A-T signals for both the page author and the overall website.</li>
          <li>Check external reputation of the site and author using independent sources.</li>
          <li>Assign a Page Quality rating from Lowest to Highest.</li>
          <li>Evaluate how well the result satisfies the specific query (Needs Met rating).</li>
        </ol>
        <p>Raters evaluate hundreds of query-result pairs. Aggregate scores across thousands of raters surface patterns that Google's data science teams use to test whether algorithm changes move results in the right direction.</p>

        <h2 id="types">E-E-A-T: the core quality framework</h2>
        <p>E-E-A-T is the most actionable framework inside the guidelines. It stands for:</p>

        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Signal</th><th>What it means</th><th>How to demonstrate it</th></tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr class="row-highlight">
                <td><strong>Experience</strong></td>
                <td>First-hand personal involvement with the topic</td>
                <td>Author bios noting direct experience; original photos; personal case studies</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><strong>Expertise</strong></td>
                <td>Demonstrable knowledge and skill</td>
                <td>Credentials, certifications, depth of coverage, accurate technical detail</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><strong>Authoritativeness</strong></td>
                <td>Recognition as a go-to source by others</td>
                <td>Backlinks from credible sites, citations, press mentions, external reviews</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><strong>Trustworthiness</strong></td>
                <td>Accuracy, security, transparency, reliability</td>
                <td>HTTPS, clear ownership, cited sources, correction policies, contact info</td>
              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <p>Trustworthiness is the most important of the four — the guidelines explicitly state that a page with low trust cannot have high E-E-A-T regardless of other signals.</p>

        <h2 id="examples">Real examples of how the guidelines affect rankings</h2>
        <p>The guidelines' influence shows up most clearly during Core Updates.</p>

        <h3>1. Medical content and YMYL</h3>
        <p>After the August 2018 Core Update (nicknamed "Medic"), health sites that lacked clear author credentials, medical reviewer attribution, and cited sources dropped significantly. Sites that added doctor bylines, cited peer-reviewed studies, and built transparent about-us pages recovered. The guidelines' YMYL and E-E-A-T standards had been encoded into the algorithm.</p>

        <h3>2. Product reviews and Experience</h3>
        <p>The 2021-2022 Product Reviews updates targeted thin reviews written without actual product use. The guidelines had long defined "experience" as a quality signal. Sites that included original product photos, specific test results, and genuine pros/cons gained rankings; affiliate thin-review sites lost them.</p>

        <h3>3. Helpful Content System and Needs Met</h3>
        <p>The 2022 Helpful Content System targeted content written primarily for search engines, not users. This directly mirrors the Needs Met rating in the guidelines — content that "Fully Meets" user needs scores high, while content satisfying the search query only superficially does not.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Search Quality Rater Guidelines vs. Google's ranking factors — what's the difference?</h2>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Search Quality Rater Guidelines</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Human evaluation framework for quality signals</li>
              <li>170+ pages of explicit definitions</li>
              <li>Publicly available and updated annually</li>
              <li>Used to train and validate algorithm changes</li>
              <li>Defines what quality should look like in principle</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Google Ranking Factors</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Automated signals processed by the algorithm</li>
              <li>200+ signals, most never disclosed publicly</li>
              <li>Constantly updated without public notice</li>
              <li>What the algorithm actually measures in practice</li>
              <li>Proxy signals for the quality the guidelines define</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">7 best practices based on the Search Quality Rater Guidelines</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Name your authors and list their credentials.</strong> Raters research author reputation. An anonymous byline is a trust penalty. Include name, role, relevant experience, and links to external profiles.</li>
          <li><strong>Research your site's external reputation.</strong> Raters look you up on independent sites. If your brand has no press mentions, reviews, or third-party citations, your authoritativeness is unverifiable.</li>
          <li><strong>Apply the highest E-E-A-T standards to YMYL content.</strong> If your pages touch health, finance, safety, or legal topics, thin or generic content is graded as Lowest or Low quality. Commission credentialed authors or add credentialed reviewers.</li>
          <li><strong>Make main content primary, supplementary content secondary.</strong> Ads, sidebars, and navigation that distract from or obscure main content lower page quality ratings.</li>
          <li><strong>Verify AI-generated content for accuracy.</strong> The guidelines treat factual errors as a trust signal. All content — human or AI-authored — needs accuracy review before publication.</li>
          <li><strong>Cite real sources.</strong> Evidence-based claims with external citations score better for trustworthiness than unsupported assertions.</li>
          <li><strong>Satisfy the full intent behind the query.</strong> Think about whether a rater would mark your page "Fully Meets" or "Partially Meets" the query. If the answer is partially, the content is incomplete.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — confusing rater guidelines with ranking factors</div>
          <p>Quality Raters don't rank pages. If you obsess over gaming the rater framework without building genuine expertise and trust, the algorithm still won't rank you. The guidelines describe quality — the algorithm attempts to measure it. Build the real thing.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common mistakes when applying the guidelines</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Adding credentials only to hide them.</strong> Burying author bios in footers or using schema without visible bylines doesn't satisfy raters who scan the page visually.</li>
          <li><strong>Treating YMYL as just a content niche.</strong> YMYL applies to any content that could significantly impact a user's health, finances, safety, or wellbeing — not just dedicated medical or finance sites.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring supplementary content.</strong> Aggressive ads, pop-ups, and sidebars that prevent access to main content are explicitly flagged in the guidelines as quality-lowering signals.</li>
          <li><strong>Assuming one core update recovery fixes everything.</strong> The guidelines are updated annually. What satisfied raters in 2022 may not fully satisfy them in 2026.</li>
          <li><strong>Confusing Page Quality with Needs Met.</strong> A technically well-produced page can still fail the Needs Met rating if it doesn't actually answer the specific query it ranks for.</li>
        </ul>

